-- Rung 2 of actor-indexed actions: a PARTY may only be obligated to perform its
-- OWN actions (party / action-index agreement). See
-- specs/todo/DEONTIC-PARTY-ACTION-AGREEMENT-SPEC.md.
--
-- NOTE: this exercises the TYPE-INDEXED encoding (Action who; DEONTIC Eater
-- (Action Drinker)), which is DEPRECATED as a surface — new models should use
-- value-actors (doc/concepts/legal-modeling/actors-and-actions.md). Kept as a
-- regression test for the still-operational rung-2 check.
--
-- The contract type `DEONTIC Eater (Action Drinker)` is incoherent: the party is
-- an `Eater`, but the action is actor-indexed to `Drinker`. The action itself is
-- type-correct for this (incoherent) contract — `Drink` *is* an `Action Drinker`,
-- so rung 1 (the declared-action-type check) is satisfied — yet the obligation
-- pairs an Eater party with a Drinker action, which rung 2 rejects.
--
-- This needs no GADTs or dependent types: the actor index is an ordinary HM type
-- argument, so the check is one nominal type-equality between the party type and
-- the action's index.

DECLARE Eater   IS ONE OF AnEater
DECLARE Drinker IS ONE OF ADrinker

DECLARE Action who HAS `verb` IS A STRING

GIVETH AN Action Drinker
Drink MEANS Action WITH `verb` IS "drink"

-- An Eater party bound to a Drinker action: rejected by party/action agreement.
GIVETH A DEONTIC Eater (Action Drinker)
`eater bound to drinker action` MEANS PARTY AnEater MUST Drink WITHIN 30
